commentBody:
@Steve L 

“Some missteps there were ELEC for ECON and EPA for DEA (DOLLY fixed that fast!)”

Same here. DOLLY PARTON wasn’t a gimme for me, though I feel like I have heard that quote before.

@Murhatroid 

I looked it up last night.  I thought, because of the etymology, they were the same thing.  Turns out, capellini are a bit thicker than ANGEL HAIR, which are capelli d'angelo in Italian.  




Thankfully, no emu hair.

@JohnWM 
It’s my iPad’s autocorrect, my autodon’tcheckfortypos, and my congenital need to show I know when an apostrophe should be used, that has led to all this autocomment about that more violent mishap.

kkseattle, per slug bug, maybe a new variant: my typo bugs me, so I’m gonna slug myself and my iPad. :-)

@Bella Romain 

I beg to differ. I'm 10 years past retirement age, and manage to keep up (somewhat) with slang terms and modern minutia. I don't use the terms but rarely, if at all. It helps to have granddaughters, and a habit of scrolling the web to keep one aware of how the language is changing and what some of the currently popular topics. However, I still learn things from the crossword frequently.

I don't feel excluded by the current crosswords any more by language or pop culture than I do for TV trivia (admittedly one of my weak points) or NY locations/neighborhoods. I still have managed a very long streak of puzzle completions.

@Mean Old Lady 
It was beret for me too for far too long. I didn’t know what a DERBY was.
Also with you on towelling diapers. Disposables were all the rage when I had my kids, but it felt wrong to shove all this stuff into landfill. I got a lot of stick for using nappies (the mess! The washing!) but I can feel environmentally smug now. Plus the modern ones are a lot easier to handle.

@Janine

Yeah, PADIDDLE was new to me. 

In addition to punch buggy and I spy I also remember playing prairie bingo on interminable drives across the prairies visiting family out there. My aunt would give each kid (as we jumped unbelted around the back seat of a land yacht) a hand drawn bingo card with pictures of things you’d commonly see on the prairies — silo, hay stack, barn, cow, horse, tractor, etc. me, the poor city boy, didn’t do too well.

@Mike

Other folks' pun attempts pail in comparison to yours. You always go deep.

You rope us in, and always… wet our appetites for more.

@William Schrader 

Sorry to hear that you found this so hard. 

Have you tried setting the puzzle aside for a few hours (or even longer)? Sometimes that really helps.

@Jess R - You're a brave person, Jess! Just know that most of us are OK with words appearing in a puzzle that are not in our own personal lexicons. I welcome them! 

I also welcome entries that do not cater to my own parochial interests. 

Bring on more like this!

@Jess R 
Waiting for you to construct more. Enjoyed your puzzle very much. 

I hadn't thought about the car game in decades. It was a nice trigger to remember those days. BTW, we called it popeyes back in olden days around the the Smokey Mountains.

@Bob

Sings "🎶SpoiLING, SpoilEEEEEENG🎶" to the tune of 'Jolene'...

I'm not making fun of your comment at all, I'd have been v annoyed if I'd gone to the column for selective hints before completing the puzzle and seen a visual spoiler.

@Roger
"[insert colour] punch buggy [JAB PASSENGER OF CHOICE], no punch-backs" 
Valid only on vw bugs.

@William this is a good wholesome response to a crossword with fill outside of your lexicon - which is funny, because someone on the cusp of millenial and gen z ( * shudders * ), i almost always do not get the latter's slang or references!
Too many people just complain and say the puzzle is not good because it doesn't speak to their generation enough. 
Just wanted to say thanks!

@CalGal 
I really must review my posts with more care.
How auto correct got "much worried" from what I intended to write is beyond me. I meant that Dolly is much wittier than Ms. Harry, who always seems so serious.

@Eva H. 
The comments section has concluded that you are wrong on all three counts.

Though I wouldn't be too hard on yourself for not being aware of LOL CAT.  It is not possible for one person to  know everything.  ;)

@MAR1

Definitely Slug Bug. Far more mellifluous and, dare I say, “punchy?” 

We took our feet off of the floor when we drove over a Mannix bridge (bridge with a metal grid deck, as seen in the opening credits of Mannix.)
